minals has also routinized killing, ironically making the city feel safer for most residents. In a fractured urban security environment, where killing mirrors patterns of inequitable urbanization and historical exclusion along class, gender, and racial lines, Denyer Willis's research finds that the city’s cyclical periods of peace and violence can best be understood through an unspoken but mutually observed consensus on the right to kill. This consensus hinges on common notions and street-level practices of who can die, where, how, and by whom, revealing an empirically distinct configuration of authority that Denyer Willis calls sovereignty by consensus.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHomicide investigationxBrazilxSão Paulo. 0aHomicide investigationzBrazilzSão Paulo. 0aHomicide investigationzBrazilzSão Paulo. 0aHomicidexBrazilxSão Paulo. 0aHomicidezBrazilzSão Paulo. 0aHomicidezBrazilzSão Paulo. 0aOrganized crimexBrazilxSão PauloxBrazilxSão Paulo. 0aOrganized crimezBrazilzSão Paulo. 0aOrganized crimezBrazilzSão Paulo. 0aPolicexBrazilxSão Paulo. 0aPolicezBrazilzSão Paulo. 0aPolicezBrazilzSão Paulo. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096113540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961135423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520961135/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles